value.value: A congenital metabolic disorder characterized by a deficiency in the enzyme ferrochelatase, which occurs in cattle.
Lymphosarcoma that occurs in a cow.
A myxoma that occurs in the rectum of a cow.
A neoplasm that occurs in dogs.

An osteosarcoma of mesenchymal origin in a dog. It is the most common bone cancer in dogs, most often developing in the limbs of large or giant breed dogs. The morphologic and biologic behavior of canine osteosarcomas is similar to that of human osteosarcomas.

Melanoma occurring in a dog. It is the most common malignant tumor found in the mouths of dogs and also occurs frequently on the digits. All canine melanomas are locally invasive and malignant canine melanomas show a high rate of metastasis. Melanoma in dogs has been established as a relevant model for human melanoma.

Hemangiosarcoma occurring in a dog. It is an incurable tumor of vascular endothelial cells and occurs more commonly in dogs beyond middle age, and is especially common in certain breeds. Most hemangiosarcomas do not have a known cause.
Mammary carcinoma occurring in a dog.

An acute or chronic malignant (clonal) hematologic disorder, arising from hematopoietic stem cells in dogs. It is characterized by the presence of primitive or atypical myeloid or lymphoid cells in the bone marrow and the blood.
A malignant lymphoproliferative disorder that affects dogs. It is characterized by the clonal proliferation of B- or T-lymphocytes in the lymph nodes, bone marrow, and/or extranodal sites.
A malignant epithelial neoplasm arising from the prostate gland of a dog.
A malignant neoplasm that affects dogs, characterized by the presence of malignant cells with morphologic and immunophenotypic characteristics similar to those seen in mature histiocytes.
A malignant neoplasm that affects dogs, arising from transitional epithelium.
A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm that affects dogs. It arises from muscle, fat, fibrous tissue, bone, cartilage, and blood vessels.
A tumor composed of mast cells that occurs in dogs.
A brain or spinal cord tumor arising from glial cells that occurs in dogs.
A malignant tumor arising from hepatocytes that occurs in dogs.
A carcinoma that arises from the lung in dogs and is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular epithelial cells.
A malignant mesenchymal neoplasm arising from skeletal muscle that occurs in dogs.
Adeonocarcinoma of the thyroid gland occurring in a dog.
Soft tissue sarcoma occurring in a dog.
Oral squamous cell carcinoma that occurs in a dog.
Pancreatic carcinoma that occurs in a dog.
A tumor arising from odontogenic epithelium and occurs in a dog.
An adenoma arising from the mammary gland of a dog.
A gastrointestinal stromal tumor occurring in a dog.
A granular cell tumor occurring in a dog.
Langerhans cell histiocytosis occurring in a dog.
A nephroblastoma occurring in a dog.
Thyroid gland medullary carcinoma occurring in a dog.
A sexually transmitted tumor arising from histiocytes and occurring in dogs.
Sebaceous epithelioma occurring in a dog.
A melanoma that affects the lip and/or oral cavity of a dog.
Cutaneous T-cell lymphoma occurring in a dog.
Neoplasm that occurs in a horse.
Melanoma that occurs in a horse.
Lymphoma that occurs in a horse.
A fibroblastic tumor that occurs in the skin of a horse.
Transitional cell carcinoma that occurs in a horse.
Neoplasm that occurs in a cat.
A lymphoma that occurs in cats. It is associated with exposure to feline leukemia virus and feline immunodeficiency virus.
Mammary carcinoma occurring in a cat.
Oral squamous cell carcinoma that occurs in a cat.
Osteosarcoma that occurs in a cat.
Bronchioloalveolar lung carcinoma that occurs in a cat.
Fibrosarcoma that occurs in a cat.
Erythroleukemia that occurs in a cat.
Reticulum cell sarcoma that occurs in a cat.
A T-cell leukemia in which there is a persistent increase in the number of large granular lymphocytes in the peripheral blood and occurring in a cat.
A malignant, usually aggressive tumor composed of atypical, neoplastic melanocytes that occurs in a cat.
